//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: is a marker, so it cannot be implemented

// A marker is satisfied by a rule the compiler applies to a type's structure — `Ord` holds
// for a type whose parts are all ordered — so there is nothing for an impl to supply.
//
// Writing one used to be accepted in silence. A marker declares no methods, so the impl had
// nothing to leave unimplemented and no arity to get wrong; it sat inert while reading, to
// anyone scanning the file, as though it granted the bound. `satisfies_marker` answers from
// the compiler's rule and never consults the impl table, so the impl could not have taken
// effect even in principle.
//
// That is the shape worth rejecting: not a wrong answer, but a declaration that looks
// load-bearing and is not. `decisions.md` recorded this as unwritable; it was writable.

use std::io;

record Pair { a: i64, b: i64 }

impl Ord for Pair {}

fn main() {
    io::println("this must not compile");
}
